<section class="card">
  <h2>What Touchstone Gold Is Best For</h2>

  <p>
    Touchstone Gold is best for gardeners who want a beet with golden flesh, mild flavor, and less red staining during prep. It is useful when you want beets for salads, roasting, or mixed-color harvests.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is not the beet to choose just because you want the most traditional red beet flavor and color. Touchstone Gold is more about a different kitchen experience: bright roots, a gentler look on the plate, and less mess on cutting boards and hands.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Is Touchstone Gold Good for Short Seasons?</h2>

  <p>
    Yes. Touchstone Gold can be a strong short-season beet because it matures in roughly the same window as many standard garden beets and can be planted in cool spring conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    The main thing to watch is steady growth. Golden beets still need enough time, moisture, and space to make good roots. If they are crowded or stressed, the harvest may be small even when the calendar says the crop should be ready.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, Touchstone Gold is usually easier to fit than heat-loving crops because it does not need a long run of warm nights. It can also be part of a fall planting plan where the season is long enough.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When to Plant Touchstone Gold</h2>

  <p>
    Touchstone Gold is usually direct sown in early spring once the soil can be worked. Beets tolerate cool conditions better than summer crops, so they can often go into the garden before beans, cucumbers, tomatoes, or peppers.
  </p>

  <p>
    For fall harvests, sow in late summer with enough time for roots to size before hard frost. In short-season gardens, that late-summer window may be brief, especially if spring crops are still occupying the bed.
  </p>

  <p>
    For local timing, use the <a href="https://growbydate.com/crops/beets/">beet growing guide</a> and your own frost dates. The right sowing date depends on soil readiness in spring and how quickly cold weather returns in fall.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Grow Touchstone Gold</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start with loose soil:</strong> Beets grow better when roots can expand without hitting compacted layers.</li>
    <li><strong>Sow evenly:</strong> Plant beet seed at a consistent depth and spacing so thinning is easier later.</li>
    <li><strong>Thin seedlings:</strong> Beet seeds are often clusters, so one seed can produce several seedlings.</li>
    <li><strong>Water regularly:</strong> Even moisture helps roots size up and keeps texture more reliable.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep weeds down:</strong> Young beets do not compete well when weeds crowd the row.</li>
    <li><strong>Harvest some greens lightly:</strong> The greens are edible, but taking too many leaves can slow root growth.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Harvest and Use</h2>

  <p>
    Touchstone Gold can be harvested when roots reach a useful size, often when they are still small to medium. The roots are especially good for roasting, slicing into salads, or adding color without the deep red stain of standard beets.
  </p>

  <p>
    Like other beets, quality is usually better before roots become oversized. If you want tender roots, harvest steadily rather than waiting for every beet to become large.
  </p>

  <p>
    For short-term storage, remove the tops and keep the roots cold and humid. Golden beets can store, but many gardeners grow them mainly for fresh use and mixed harvests rather than long winter storage.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Growing Touchstone Gold</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Not thinning seedlings:</strong> Crowded golden beets may make lots of leaves and disappointing roots.</li>
    <li><strong>Letting young plants compete with weeds:</strong> Early weed pressure can slow the crop before roots begin to size.</li>
    <li><strong>Planting into poor soil:</strong> Compacted or dry soil makes it harder to get smooth, usable roots.</li>
    <li><strong>Waiting too long to harvest:</strong> Smaller and medium roots are often better for texture and flavor.</li>
    <li><strong>Expecting red beet behavior in the kitchen:</strong> Touchstone Gold is useful partly because it looks and handles differently.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Touchstone Gold vs Other Beet Varieties</h2>

  <p>
    Compared with Detroit Dark Red and other red beets, Touchstone Gold offers a milder-looking, less staining root. It is a good companion variety if you want mixed beet colors or if red beets feel too messy for everyday cooking.
  </p>

  <p>
    Red beets may still be the better choice for traditional pickling, classic beet dishes, or storage-focused planting. Touchstone Gold earns its space when color, fresh eating, and kitchen convenience matter more than tradition.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Who Should Grow Touchstone Gold?</h2>

  <p>
    Touchstone Gold is a good choice if you like beets but want something brighter and less messy than standard red types. It works well for gardeners who cook fresh from the garden and want roots that look good in mixed vegetable dishes.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is also a useful beet for short-season gardens because it can be direct sown early and does not depend on summer heat. The crop still needs thinning and steady moisture, so it rewards gardeners who can give the row a little attention.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>

  <p>
    Touchstone Gold can be a good choice when the timing matches your spring conditions, growing season length, and expected fall frost. The exact planting window still depends on where you garden.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before choosing a planting date, check your local frost window and crop timing. A variety can fit short seasons well and still underperform if it is planted too late, started too late indoors, or grown in poor conditions.
  </p>

